;;; std/sha256/sha256.weld.shard -- THE BLOCK WELD (docs/IMP.md I2e-1):
;;; the generated ISA legs (impgen_wasm_out's imp_w_shblock,
;;; impgen_x86_out's imp_x_shblock -- machine eval of the translated
;;; block body = exit adapter of the imp run) compose with the hand
;;; walk (isha_block_walk -- the imp run lands on spec shapes), so ONE
;;; compression block's MACHINE code lands on spec shapes on BOTH
;;; targets: shw_wblock / shw_xblock.
;;;
;;; The output value is named once (shw_sm / shw_r / shw_locals /
;;; shw_mem, spelled exactly as the walk's RHS trees) so downstream
;;; consumers (the I2e driver composition) speak a compact vocabulary.
;;;
;;; SPELLING BRIDGES (the examples/weld_probe.shard measurement): the
;;; rewriter matches syntactically, never modulo computation. The walk
;;; is stated over the sibling's SOURCE spelling (builder calls); the
;;; wasm out's imp body is the evaluated NORMAL FORM; the x86 out's is
;;; the chunked rest-fn chain. All three are closed ground data, so
;;; the weld carries byte-copies of each spelling as local nullary fns
;;; ((inline ...) resolves against the file's OWN fns only -- the I1b
;;; bridge-file precedent) and crosses spellings by compute-both
;;; bridge equations that meet at the shared normal form.
;;;
;;; Fuel: the outs state the imp side at (S^ 297 c2); the walk needs
;;; (S^ 400 d) -- the citations instantiate c2 := (S^ 103 d), and
;;; (S^ 297 (S^ 103 d)) IS (S^ 400 d) as a tree.

